{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f8f55ca4-95f8-4de3-93f1-24598101c860","content":"The standard approach is to **introduce a file system abstraction**:\n\n1. **Define an interface** for the operations you use:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\n2. **Create a real implementation** for production:\n\n```csharp\npublic class FileSystem : IFileSystem\n{\n    public string ReadAllText(string path) => File.ReadAllText(path);\n    public void WriteAllText(string path, string contents) => File.WriteAllText(path, contents);\n    public bool DirectoryExists(string path) => Directory.Exists(path);\n}\n```\n\n3. **Inject `IFileSystem`** into classes that need it, then **mock/fake it** in tests.\n\n**Alternatively**, use the built-in `System.IO.Abstractions` NuGet package — it provides `IFileSystem` with full coverage of `File`, `Directory`, `Path`, etc., plus a `MockFileSystem` for testing out of the box.\n\n```\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions\ndotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cfb6eb75-793a-4eb1-b6d3-95096e9edd21","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to make file system operations (`File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, `Directory.Exists`) testable in their .NET project. This is a common software design question about dependency injection and abstraction.\n\nI don't need to look at any files for this - it's a general software engineering question. I'll provide a concise answer about the standard approach.","outputTokens":400,"requestId":"BD1C:61C51:1DA72AB:2180133:6A07CAAF"},"id":"93849ee5-299a-406d-944f-f0b289460107","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:39:05.151Z","parentId":"9f21f750-69ae-48c0-8bcc-349e85cd6bf0"}
